docs.abstract: Spike Lee’s new joint is an anguished, funny, violent argument with and about American history, with an unforgettable performance from Delroy Lindo at its heart.
docs.snippet: Spike Lee’s new joint is an anguished, funny, violent argument with and about American history, with an unforgettable performance from Delroy Lindo at its heart.
docs.lead_paragraph: Spike Lee’s career can be described as a lover’s quarrel with American movies — and with America, too. As he has demonstrated his mastery of established genres (the biopic, the musical, the cop movie, the combat picture, and so on), he has also reinvented them, pointing out blind spots and filling in gaps. His critique of Hollywood’s long history of ignoring and distorting black lives has altered the way we look at movies. His attempts to expand the frame and correct the record have changed the course of the cultural mainstream.

headline.main: ‘Da 5 Bloods’ Review: Black Lives Mattered in Vietnam, Too
headline.print_headline: In Vietnam,  Black Lives  Mattered, Too

docs.abstract: Protests over George Floyd’s death have reached small towns like Petal, Miss., a predominantly white community where neighbors are confronting one another and talking about racial divides.
docs.snippet: Protests over George Floyd’s death have reached small towns like Petal, Miss., a predominantly white community where neighbors are confronting one another and talking about racial divides.
docs.lead_paragraph: PETAL, Miss. — In what has become a morning routine, Lorraine Bates walks the seven-tenths of a mile to City Hall from her house in Petal, Miss. In the first days of demonstrations, she joined some 200 other protesters, many of them white, chanting and waving “Black Lives Matter” posters. But there were also times when it was just her and a groundskeeper who mowed around her.

headline.main: A Small Mississippi Town, ‘Asking for a Breath’ After Mayor’s Remarks Unleash Protests
headline.print_headline: Racial Fault Line Exposed, Mississippi Town Comes Together

docs.abstract: Essential reading from T’s archive, including pieces on how L.G.B.T.Q. culture has re-envisioned the worlds of food, art and entertainment.
docs.snippet: Essential reading from T’s archive, including pieces on how L.G.B.T.Q. culture has re-envisioned the worlds of food, art and entertainment.
docs.lead_paragraph: Stonewall was a riot. This has become the de facto slogan to describe the series of early-summer 1969 demonstrations that took place in front of New York City’s Stonewall Inn, the gay bar that became a battleground for the movement that catalyzed L.G.B.T.Q. rights in this country. Indeed, this historic rebellion is the reason we celebrate Pride Month each June. But as America rages on — against an uncured pandemic as well as its aftereffects, and for justice following the deaths of George Floyd, Breonna Taylor and others at the hands of police — that phrase, “Stonewall was a riot,” has taken on new resonance: It’s an assertion that fighting, not partying, is the root of our story. And this year, as many join in protests chanting “Black lives matter,” we are reminded that the Stonewall liberation was led by trans women of color, including Marsha P. Johnson and Sylvia Rivera, two activists whom city officials decided last year to honor with a monument, after decades of progress being too often attributed to mostly white gay men.

headline.main: For Pride Month, Eight Stories About Queer Power and Defiance
